com.googlecode.biscotti.collect

Class TreeDeque<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      • java.util.AbstractQueue<E>
        • com.googlecode.biscotti.collect.TreeQueue<E>
          • com.googlecode.biscotti.collect.TreeDeque<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - the type of elements held in this deque
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    SortedCollection<E>, Serializable, Cloneable, Iterable<E>, Collection<E>, Deque<E>, Queue<E>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    TreeBoundedDeque

    public class TreeDeque<E>
extends TreeQueue<E>
implements Deque<E>
    An unbounded double-ended priority queue (also known as a Deque) based on a modified Red-Black Tree. The elements of this deque are sorted according to their natural ordering, or by an explicit Comparator provided at creation. Inserting null elements will fail cleanly and safely leaving this deque unmodified. Querying for null elements is allowed. Attempting to insert non-comparable elements will result in a ClassCastException . The addFirst(E), addLast(E), offerFirst(E), offerLast(E), and push(E) operations are not supported.

    This deque is ordered from least to greatest with respect to the specified ordering. Elements with equal priority are ordered according to their insertion order.

    The iterator() and descendingIterator() methods return fail-fast iterators which are guaranteed to traverse the elements of the deque in priority and reverse priority order, respectively. Attempts to modify the elements in this deque at any time after an iterator is created, in any way except through the iterator's own remove method, will result in a ConcurrentModificationException.

    This deque is not thread-safe. If multiple threads modify this deque concurrently it must be synchronized externally.

    Implementation Note: This implementation uses a comparator (whether or not one is explicitly provided) to maintain priority order, and equals when testing for element equality. The ordering imposed by the comparator is not required to be consistent with equals. Given a comparator c, for any two elements e1 and e2 such that c.compare(e1, e2) == 0 it is not necessarily true that e1.equals(e2) == true.

    The underlying Red-Black Tree provides the following worst case running time (where n is the size of this list and m is the size of the specified collection):

    Method Running Time
    addAll(Collection)
    containsAll(Collection)
    retainAll(Collection)
    removeAll(Collection)     		O(m log n)
    add(E)
    contains(Object)
    offer(E)
    remove(Object)     		O(log n)
    element()
    isEmpty()
    peek()
    poll()
    remove()
    size()
    getFirst()
    getLast()
    peekFirst()
    peekLast()
    pollFirst()
    pollLast()
    pop()
    removeFirst()
    removeLast()
    clear()     		O(1)

    Refer to TreeQueue for a comparison with java.util.PriorityQueue.

    Note: This deque uses the same ordering rules as java.util.PriorityQueue. In comparison it offers element operations at both ends, ordered traversals via its iterators, and faster overall running time.

      • create

        public static <E> TreeDeque<E> create(Iterable<? extends E> elements)
        Creates a new TreeDeque containing the elements of the specified Iterable. If the specified iterable is an instance of SortedSet, PriorityQueue or SortedCollection this deque will be ordered according to the same ordering. Otherwise, this deque will be ordered according to the natural ordering of its elements.
        Parameters:
        elements - the iterable whose elements are to be placed into the deque
        Returns:
        a new TreeDeque containing the elements of the specified iterable
        Throws:
        ClassCastException - if elements of the specified iterable cannot be compared to one another according to the this deque's ordering
        NullPointerException - if any of the elements of the specified iterable or the iterable itself is null
